explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER: This is a macro used directly in the target function; its preprocessor expansion becomes part of the function body. To determine whether the target uses any compiler/language extensions you must inspect the macro definition (it might use GCC/MSC extensions such as statement-expressions, typeof, __extension__, __attribute__, inline asm, variadic macro tricks, etc.).

OS_printf: The static call graph shows OS_printf is invoked by the target (most likely via OS_CHECK_POINTER). Its prototype or implementation may include compiler-specific attributes (e.g. __attribute__((format(...))) or other extensions) or use variadic/extension features; the declaration/definition must be checked.

OS_ObjectIdFindByName: This function is called by the target. Its prototype/definition must be inspected to see whether it (or its parameter types) use any language/compiler extensions (attributes on the function, non-standard parameter types, inline asm, compiler-specific qualifiers, etc.) because those could make the target’s call rely on extensions.

LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: This macro/enum/constant is passed to OS_ObjectIdFindByName. Its definition might expand to an expression or type that uses language extensions (e.g. compiler-specific constants, cast expressions, or macros that embed extension constructs), so it must be examined.

osal_id_t: The type of the out-parameter queue_id. Its typedef/definition must be checked to ensure it is a standard C type and does not use compiler-specific extensions (e.g. __int128, attributes on the typedef, anonymous structs/unions with extension keywords, etc.).

int32: The return_code/local integer type used in the function. The typedef/definition of int32 must be inspected to ensure it is a standard, portable typedef (not a compiler-specific extended type or defined using compiler-specific attributes or keywords).
